    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Is a Sandbox Environment?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A sandbox environment is an isolated execution context that restricts what a running process can see, read, write, or communicate with. For AI agents that run tool calls or execute model-generated code, the sandbox is the boundary that prevents a misbehaving or adversarial task from reaching sensitive files, internal networks, or other tenants."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sandbox environments form a spectrum from lightweight process separation (fast, weak isolation) to hardware-level virtual machine boundaries (slow, strong isolation). The right choice depends on who supplies the code, how many tenants share the host, and how sensitive the host environment is."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Sandbox environment spectrum: in-process \u2192 subprocess \u2192 Linux namespaces \u2192 Docker \u2192 VM/gVisor"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subprocess Sandboxes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The simplest sandbox is a child process: fork the interpreter, run the code, collect stdout/stderr, and terminate. The child inherits the parent's environment unless you explicitly strip it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import subprocess\nimport sys\nimport os\n\ndef run_in_subprocess(code: str, timeout: int = 10) -> dict:\n    # Strip the parent environment \u2014 do not inherit secrets\n    clean_env = {\n        \"PATH\": \"/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\",\n        \"HOME\": \"/tmp\",\n        \"LANG\": \"C.UTF-8\",\n    }\n\n    proc = subprocess.run(\n        [sys.executable, \"-c\", code],\n        capture_output=True,\n        text=True,\n        timeout=timeout,\n        env=clean_env,                    # no API keys, no AWS creds\n        cwd=\"/tmp\",                       # start in a neutral directory\n    )\n    return {\n        \"stdout\": proc.stdout[:8192],\n        \"stderr\": proc.stderr[:2048],\n        \"returncode\": proc.returncode,\n        \"error\": None if proc.returncode == 0 else proc.stderr[:1024],\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subprocess sandboxes do not isolate the filesystem \u2014 the child can read /etc/passwd and /home/user/.ssh unless you add OS-level controls. They are appropriate for agents running in a controlled developer environment, not for public-facing services."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Linux Namespace Sandboxes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Linux namespaces let you give a process its own view of the filesystem, network, and process tree without the overhead of a full container runtime. The bubblewrap tool (used by Flatpak and Nix) wraps namespace creation into a single command:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import subprocess\nimport tempfile\nimport os\n\ndef run_in_bubblewrap(code: str, timeout: int = 15) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Run code in a Linux namespace sandbox via bubblewrap.\n    Requires: apt install bubblewrap\n    \"\"\"\n    with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(suffix=\".py\", mode=\"w\", delete=False) as f:\n        f.write(code)\n        script = f.name\n\n    try:\n        cmd = [\n            \"bwrap\",\n            \"--ro-bind\", \"/usr\", \"/usr\",           # read-only /usr\n            \"--ro-bind\", \"/lib\", \"/lib\",\n            \"--ro-bind\", \"/lib64\", \"/lib64\",\n            \"--ro-bind\", \"/bin\", \"/bin\",\n            \"--proc\", \"/proc\",\n            \"--dev\", \"/dev\",\n            \"--tmpfs\", \"/tmp\",                     # writable tmpfs\n            \"--unshare-all\",                       # new namespaces for everything\n            \"--share-net\",                         # remove to block network\n            \"--die-with-parent\",\n            \"--ro-bind\", script, \"/script.py\",\n            \"python3\", \"/script.py\",\n        ]\n        proc = subprocess.run(\n            cmd, capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=timeout\n        )\n        return {\n            \"stdout\": proc.stdout[:8192],\n            \"stderr\": proc.stderr[:2048],\n            \"error\": None if proc.returncode == 0 else proc.stderr[:1024],\n        }\n    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:\n        return {\"stdout\": \"\", \"stderr\": \"\", \"error\": f\"Timed out after {timeout}s\"}\n    finally:\n        os.unlink(script)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Docker Container Sandboxes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Docker (or any OCI-compatible runtime) creates a container with a separate filesystem, network stack, and cgroup-enforced resource limits. It is the standard choice for production code execution sandboxes:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import subprocess\nimport json\n\ndef run_in_docker(\n    code: str,\n    image: str = \"python:3.12-slim\",\n    timeout: int = 15,\n    network: str = \"none\",\n    memory: str = \"128m\",\n) -> dict:\n    cmd = [\n        \"docker\", \"run\", \"--rm\",\n        \"--network\", network,\n        \"--memory\", memory,\n        \"--memory-swap\", memory,          # disable swap\n        \"--cpu-quota\", \"50000\",           # 50% of one CPU\n        \"--pids-limit\", \"64\",\n        \"--read-only\",\n        \"--tmpfs\", \"/tmp:size=32m,noexec\",\n        \"--cap-drop\", \"ALL\",\n        \"--security-opt\", \"no-new-privileges\",\n        image,\n        \"python3\", \"-c\", code,\n    ]\n    try:\n        proc = subprocess.run(\n            cmd, capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=timeout + 5\n        )\n        return {\n            \"stdout\": proc.stdout[:8192],\n            \"stderr\": proc.stderr[:2048],\n            \"error\": None if proc.returncode == 0 else proc.stderr[:1024],\n        }\n    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:\n        return {\"stdout\": \"\", \"stderr\": \"\", \"error\": f\"Timed out after {timeout}s\"}\n    except FileNotFoundError:\n        return {\"stdout\": \"\", \"stderr\": \"\", \"error\": \"Docker daemon not available\"}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pre-built Sandbox Images"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Building a custom image lets you pre-install packages (pandas, numpy, scipy) and harden the base image:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "dockerfile"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Dockerfile \u2014 minimal analysis sandbox\nFROM python:3.12-slim\n\n# Install data science libraries\nRUN pip install --no-cache-dir numpy pandas matplotlib scipy scikit-learn\n\n# Remove shells and package managers to reduce attack surface\nRUN rm -f /bin/sh /bin/bash /usr/bin/apt* /usr/bin/dpkg\n\n# Run as non-root\nRUN useradd -m sandbox\nUSER sandbox\nWORKDIR /home/sandbox\n\nENTRYPOINT [\"python3\", \"-c\"]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "gVisor and Firecracker"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For multi-tenant SaaS where users supply arbitrary code, Docker's shared kernel is a risk \u2014 a container escape vulnerability exposes all tenants. gVisor (runsc) and Firecracker provide a separate kernel per sandbox:"
          }
        ]
      },
